# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quantum-electrodynamics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] In quantum electrodynamics, the **anomalous magnetic moment** of a particle is a contribution of effects of quantum mechanics, expressed by Feynman diagrams with loops, to the magnetic moment of that particle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The *magnetic moment*, also called *magnetic dipole moment*, is a measure of the strength of a magnetic source.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The "Dirac" magnetic moment, corresponding to tree-level Feynman diagrams (which can be thought of as the classical result), can be calculated from the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] It is usually expressed in terms of the *g*-factor; the Dirac equation predicts $g=-2$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] For particles such as the electron, this classical result differs from the observed value by a small fraction of a percent.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The difference is the anomalous magnetic moment, denoted a and defined as $a={\frac {|g|-2}{2}}$ (the magnitude of g is used in the calculation since the g-factor is, in fact, negative).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The one-loop contribution to the anomalous magnetic moment—corresponding to the first and largest quantum mechanical correction—of the electron is found by calculating the vertex function shown in the adjacent diagram.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The calculation is relatively straightforward and the one-loop result is: $a_{\text{e}}={\frac {\alpha }{2\pi }}\approx 0.001\,161\,4,$ where $\alpha$ is the fine-structure constant.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] This result was first found by Julian Schwinger in 1948 and is engraved on his tombstone.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The QED prediction agrees with the experimentally measured value to more than 10 significant figures, making the magnetic moment of the electron one of the most accurately verified predictions in the history of physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] This required measuring g to an accuracy of around 1 part in 10 trillion (1013).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The anomalous magnetic moment of the muon is calculated in a similar way to the electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] Of the first two components, $a_{\mu }^{\mathrm {QED} }$ represents the photon and lepton loops, and $a_{\mu }^{\mathrm {EW} }$ the W boson, Higgs boson and Z boson loops; both can be calculated precisely from first principles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The third term, $a_{\mu }^{\mathrm {hadron} }$ , represents hadron loops; it cannot be calculated accurately from theory alone.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] It is either estimated from experimental measurements of the ratio of hadronic to muonic cross sections (*R*) in electron–antielectron (e− –e+ ) collisions, or else calculated from scratch in lattice gauge theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The E821 Experiment at Brookhaven National Laboratory (BNL) studied the precession of muon and antimuon in a constant external magnetic field as they circulated in a confining storage ring.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] In 2024, the Fermilab collaboration "Muon *g*−2" doubled the accuracy of this value over the group's previous measurements from the 2018 data set.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The data for the experiment were collected during the 2019–2020 runs.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] For a long time, experimental measurements and theoretical predictions of this quantity disagreed, making the muon's anomalous magnetic moment a long-standing discrepancy between the Standard Model and experiment.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] As of July 2017, for instance, the measurement disagreed with the Standard Model by 3.5 standard deviations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] This disagreement was seen as suggesting physics beyond the Standard Model may be having an effect, or else that the theoretical/experimental errors were not completely under control.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] In May 2025, a large international consortium of scientists reported calculations in which the estimate of the quark and gluon contributions that in earlier calculations had been based on experimental data had been replaced with from-scratch lattice QCD calculations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] This yielded $a_{\mu }=0.001\,165\,920\,33(62),$ which was compatible both with the then-best experimental data and with the final "Muon g−2" result that was published a few weeks after.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The Standard Model prediction for the tau's anomalous magnetic dipole moment is $a_{\tau }=0.001\,177\,21(5),$ while the best measured bound for $a_{\tau }$ is $a_{\tau }={0.0009}_{-0.0031}^{+0.0032},$ reported by the CMS experiment at the CERN LHC.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] Composite particles often have large anomalous magnetic moments.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The nucleons, protons and neutrons, both composed of quarks, are examples.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/anomalous-magnetic-dipole-moment] The nucleon magnetic moments are both large and were unexpected; the proton's magnetic moment is much too large for an elementary particle, while the neutron's magnetic moment was expected to be zero due to its charge being zero.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The effect was discovered in 1923 by Arthur Holly Compton while researching the scattering of X-rays by light elements, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1927.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The Compton effect significantly deviated from dominating classical theories, using both special relativity and quantum mechanics to explain the interaction between high frequency photons and charged particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Photons can interact with matter at the atomic level (e.g. photoelectric effect and Rayleigh scattering), at the nucleus, or with only an electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Pair production and the Compton effect occur at the level of the electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] When a high-frequency photon scatters due to an interaction with a charged particle, the photon's energy is reduced, and thus its wavelength is increased.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This trade-off between wavelength and energy in response to the collision is the Compton effect.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Because of conservation of energy, the energy that is lost by the photon is transferred to the recoiling particle (such an electron would be called a "Compton recoil electron").
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This implies that if the recoiling particle initially carried more energy than the photon has, the reverse would occur.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This is known as **inverse Compton scattering**, in which the scattered photon increases in energy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In Compton's original experiment (see Fig.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] 1), the energy of the X-ray photon (≈ 17 keV) was significantly larger than the binding energy of the atomic electron, so the electrons could be treated as being free after scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The amount by which the light's wavelength changes is called the **Compton shift**.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Although Compton scattering from a nucleus exists, Compton scattering usually refers to the interaction involving only the electrons of an atom.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The Compton effect was observed by Arthur Holly Compton in 1923 at Washington University in St.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Louis and further verified by his graduate student Y.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton was awarded the 1927 Nobel Prize in Physics for the discovery.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The effect is significant because it demonstrates that light cannot be explained purely as a wave phenomenon.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Thus, if we are to explain low-intensity Compton scattering, light must behave as if it consists of particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Or the assumption that the electron can be treated as free is invalid resulting in the effectively infinite electron mass equal to the nuclear mass (see e.g. the comment below on elastic scattering of X-rays being from that effect).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton's experiment convinced physicists that light can be treated as a stream of particle-like objects (quanta called photons), whose energy is proportional to the light wave's frequency.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] 2, the interaction between an electron and a photon results in the electron being given part of the energy (making it recoil), and a photon of the remaining energy being emitted in a different direction from the original, so that the overall momentum of the system is also conserved.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] If the scattered photon still has enough energy, the process may be repeated.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In this scenario, the electron is treated as free or loosely bound.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Experimental verification of momentum conservation in individual Compton scattering processes by Bothe and Geiger as well as by Compton and Simon has been important in disproving the BKS theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton scattering is commonly described as inelastic scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This is because, unlike the more common Thomson scattering that happens at the low-energy limit, the energy in the scattered photon in Compton scattering is less than the energy of the incident photon.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] As the electron is typically weakly bound to the atom, the scattering can be viewed from either the perspective of an electron in a potential well, or as an atom with a small ionization energy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In the former perspective, energy of the incident photon is transferred to the recoil particle, but only as kinetic energy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The electron gains no internal energy, respective masses remain the same, the mark of an elastic collision.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] From this perspective, Compton scattering could be considered elastic because the internal state of the electron does not change during the scattering process.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In the latter perspective, the atom's state is changed, constituting an inelastic collision.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Whether Compton scattering is considered elastic or inelastic depends on which perspective is being used, as well as the context.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton scattering is one of four competing processes when photons interact with matter.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] At energies of a few eV to a few keV, corresponding to visible light through soft X-rays, a photon can be completely absorbed and its energy can eject an electron from its host atom, a process known as the photoelectric effect.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton scattering is the most important interaction in the intervening energy region, at photon energies greater than those typical of the photoelectric effect but less than the pair-production threshold.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] By the early 20th century, research into the interaction of X-rays with matter was well under way.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] It was observed that when X-rays of a known wavelength interact with atoms, the X-rays are scattered through an angle $\theta$ and emerge at a different wavelength related to $\theta$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Although classical electromagnetism predicted that the wavelength of scattered rays should be equal to the initial wavelength, multiple experiments had found that the wavelength of the scattered rays was longer (corresponding to lower energy) than the initial wavelength.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In 1923, Compton published a paper that explained the X-ray shift by attributing particle-like momentum to light quanta (Albert Einstein had proposed light quanta in 1905 in explaining the photo-electric effect, but Compton did not build on Einstein's work).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The energy of light quanta depends only on the frequency of the light.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In his paper, Compton derived the mathematical relationship between the shift in wavelength and the scattering angle of the X-rays by assuming that each scattered X-ray photon interacted with only one electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The quantity ⁠*h*/*m*e*c*⁠ is known as the Compton wavelength of the electron; it is equal to 2.43×10−12 m.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The wavelength shift *λ*′ − *λ* is at least zero (for *θ* = 0°) and at most twice the Compton wavelength of the electron (for *θ* = 180°).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton found that some X-rays experienced no wavelength shift despite being scattered through large angles; in each of these cases the photon failed to eject an electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Thus the magnitude of the shift is related not to the Compton wavelength of the electron, but to the Compton wavelength of the entire atom, which can be upwards of 10000 times smaller.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This is known as "coherent" scattering off the entire atom since the atom remains intact, gaining no internal excitation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In Compton's original experiments the wavelength shift given above was the directly measurable observable.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In modern experiments it is conventional to measure the energies, not the wavelengths, of the scattered photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] A photon γ with wavelength λ collides with an electron e in an atom, which is treated as being at rest.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The collision causes the electron to recoil, and a new photon *γ*′ with wavelength *λ*′ emerges at angle θ from the photon's incoming path.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Let e′ denote the electron after the collision.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton allowed for the possibility that the interaction would sometimes accelerate the electron to speeds sufficiently close to the velocity of light as to require the application of Einstein's special relativity theory to properly describe its energy and momentum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] At the conclusion of Compton's 1923 paper, he reported results of experiments confirming the predictions of his scattering formula, thus supporting the assumption that photons carry momentum as well as quantized energy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] At the start of his derivation, he had postulated an expression for the momentum of a photon from equating Einstein's already established mass-energy relationship of *E* = *mc*2 to the quantized photon energies of *hf*, which Einstein had separately postulated.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] If *mc*2 = *hf*, the equivalent photon mass must be *hf*/*c*2.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The photon's momentum is then simply this effective mass times the photon's frame-invariant velocity c.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] For a photon, its momentum $p=hf/c$ , and thus *hf* can be substituted for *pc* for all photon momentum terms which arise in course of the derivation below.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The derivation which appears in Compton's paper is more terse, but follows the same logic in the same sequence as the following derivation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The conservation of energy *E* merely equates the sum of energies before and after scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] in which **p**e is omitted as being negligible.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Equation (1) relates the various energies associated with the collision.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The electron's momentum change involves a relativistic change in the energy of the electron, so it is not simply related to the change in energy occurring in classical physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The change of the magnitude of the momentum of the photon is not just related to the change of its energy; it also involves a change in direction.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton scattering is of prime importance to radiobiology, as it is the most probable interaction of gamma rays and high energy X-rays with atoms in living beings and is applied in radiation therapy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton scattering is an important effect in gamma spectroscopy which gives rise to the Compton edge, as it is possible for the gamma rays to scatter out of the detectors used.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Compton suppression is used to detect stray scatter gamma rays to counteract this effect.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Magnetic Compton scattering is an extension of the previously mentioned technique which involves the magnetisation of a crystal sample hit with high energy, circularly polarised photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] By measuring the scattered photons' energy and reversing the magnetisation of the sample, two different Compton profiles are generated (one for spin up momenta and one for spin down momenta).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Since this scattering process is incoherent (there is no phase relationship between the scattered photons), the MCP is representative of the bulk properties of the sample and is a probe of the ground state.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This means that the MCP is ideal for comparison with theoretical techniques such as density functional theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The area under the MCP is directly proportional to the spin moment of the system and so, when combined with total moment measurements methods (such as SQUID magnetometry), can be used to isolate both the spin and orbital contributions to the total moment of a system.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The shape of the MCP also yields insight into the origin of the magnetism in the system.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Inverse Compton scattering is important in astrophysics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] In X-ray astronomy, the accretion disk surrounding a black hole is presumed to produce a thermal spectrum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The lower energy photons produced from this spectrum are scattered to higher energies by relativistic electrons in the surrounding corona.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This phenomenon is called relativistic reflection and is surmised to cause the power law component in the X-ray spectra (0.2–10 keV) of accreting black holes.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The effect is also observed when photons from the cosmic microwave background (CMB) move through the hot gas surrounding a galaxy cluster.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] The CMB photons are scattered to higher energies by the electrons in this gas, resulting in the Sunyaev–Zel'dovich effect.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Observations of the Sunyaev–Zel'dovich effect provide a nearly redshift-independent means of detecting galaxy clusters.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Some synchrotron radiation facilities scatter laser light off the stored electron beam.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] This Compton backscattering produces high energy photons in the MeV to GeV range subsequently used for nuclear physics experiments.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Non-linear inverse Compton scattering (NICS) is the scattering of multiple low-energy photons, given by an intense electromagnetic field, in a high-energy photon (X-ray or gamma ray) during the interaction with a charged particle, such as an electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] It is also called non-linear Compton scattering and multiphoton Compton scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] It is the non-linear version of inverse Compton scattering in which the conditions for multiphoton absorption by the charged particle are reached due to a very intense electromagnetic field, for example the one produced by a laser.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] Non-linear inverse Compton scattering is an interesting phenomenon for all applications requiring high-energy photons since NICS is capable of producing photons with energy comparable to the charged particle rest energy and higher.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/compton-scattering] As a consequence NICS photons can be used to trigger other phenomena such as pair production, Compton scattering, nuclear reactions, and can be used to probe non-linear quantum effects and non-linear QED.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In particle physics, the **Dirac equation** is a relativistic wave equation derived by British physicist Paul Dirac in 1928.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In its free form, or including electromagnetic interactions, it describes all spin-⁠1/2⁠ massive particles, called "Dirac particles", such as electrons and quarks for which parity is a symmetry.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] It is consistent with both the principles of quantum mechanics and the theory of special relativity, and was the first theory to fully account for special relativity in the context of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The equation is validated by its rigorous accounting of the observed fine structure of the hydrogen spectrum and has become vital in the building of the Standard Model.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The equation also implied the existence of a new form of matter, *antimatter*, previously unsuspected and unobserved.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The existence of antimatter was experimentally confirmed several years later.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] It also provided a *theoretical* justification for the introduction of several component wave functions in Pauli's phenomenological theory of spin.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The wave functions in the Dirac theory are vectors of four complex numbers (known as Dirac spinors), two of which resemble the Pauli wavefunction in the non-relativistic limit, in contrast to the Schrödinger equation, which described wave functions of only one complex value.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Moreover, in the limit of zero mass, the Dirac equation reduces to the Weyl equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In the context of quantum field theory, the Dirac equation is reinterpreted to describe quantum fields corresponding to spin-⁠1/2⁠ particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Dirac did not fully appreciate the importance of his results; however, the entailed explanation of spin as a consequence of the union of quantum mechanics and relativity—and the eventual discovery of the positron—represents one of the great triumphs of theoretical physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This accomplishment has been described as fully on par with the works of Isaac Newton, James Clerk Maxwell, and Albert Einstein before him.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The equation has been deemed by some physicists to be "the real seed of modern physics".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac equation has been described as the "centerpiece of relativistic quantum mechanics", and as "perhaps the most important [equation] in all of quantum mechanics".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The first phase in the development of quantum mechanics, lasting between 1900 and 1925, focused on explaining individual phenomena that could not be explained through classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The second phase, starting in the mid-1920s, saw the development of two systematic frameworks governing quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The first, known as matrix mechanics, uses matrices to describe physical observables; it was developed in 1925 by Werner Heisenberg, Max Born, and Pascual Jordan.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The second, known as wave mechanics, uses a wave equation known as the Schrödinger equation to describe the state of a system; it was developed the next year by Erwin Schrödinger.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] While these two frameworks were initially seen as competing approaches, they would later be shown to be equivalent.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Both these frameworks only formulated quantum mechanics in a non-relativistic setting.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This was seen as a deficiency right from the start, with Schrödinger originally attempting to formulate a relativistic version of the Schrödinger equation, in the process discovering the Klein–Gordon equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] However, after showing that this equation did not correctly reproduce the relativistic corrections to the hydrogen atom spectrum for which an exact form was known due to Arnold Sommerfeld, he abandoned his relativistic formulation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Klein–Gordon equation was also found by at least six other authors in the same year.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] During 1926 and 1927, there was a widespread effort to incorporate relativity into quantum mechanics, largely through two approaches.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The first was to consider the Klein–Gordon as the correct relativistic generalization of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Such an approach was viewed unfavourably by many leading theorists since it failed to correctly predict numerous experimental results, and more importantly it appeared difficult to reconcile with the principles of quantum mechanics as understood at the time.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] These conceptual issues primarily arose due to the presence of a second temporal derivative.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The second approach introduced relativistic effects as corrections to the known non-relativistic formulas.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This provided many provisional answers that were expected to eventually be supplanted by some yet-unknown relativistic formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] One notable result by Heisenberg and Jordan was the introduction of two terms for spin and relativity into the hydrogen Hamiltonian, allowing them to derive the first-order approximation of the Sommerfeld fine structure formula.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] A parallel development during this time was the concept of spin, first introduced in 1925 by Samuel Goudsmit and George Uhlenbeck.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Shortly after, it was conjectured by Schrödinger to be the missing link in acquiring the correct Sommerfeld formula.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In 1927, Wolfgang Pauli used the ideas of spin to find an effective theory for a nonrelativistic spin-⁠1/2⁠ particle, the Pauli equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] He did this by taking the Schrödinger equation and, rather than just assuming that the wave function depends on the physical coordinate, he also assumed that it depends on a spin coordinate that can take only two values $\pm {\tfrac {\hbar }{2}}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] While this was still a non-relativistic formulation, he believed that a fully relativistic formulation possibly required a more complicated model for the electron, one that moved beyond a point particle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] At the fifth Solvay Conference held that year, Paul Dirac was primarily concerned with the logical development of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] However, he realized that many other physicists complacently accepted the Klein–Gordon equation as a satisfactory relativistic formulation, which demanded abandoning basic principles of quantum mechanics as understood at the time, to which Dirac strongly objected.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] After his return from Brussels, Dirac focused on finding a relativistic theory for electrons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Within two months he solved the problem and published his results on January 2, 1928.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In his paper, Dirac was guided by two principles from transformation theory, the first being that the equation should be invariant under transformations of special relativity, and the second that it should transform under the transformation theory of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The latter demanded that the equation would have to be linear in temporal derivatives, so that it would admit a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] describing a particle using the wave function $\phi (t,x)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Here ${\boldsymbol {p}}^{2}=p_{1}^{2}+p_{2}^{2}+p_{3}^{2}$ is the square of the momentum, m is the rest mass of the particle, c is the speed of light, and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The naive way to get an equation linear in the time derivative is to essentially consider the square root of both sides.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] However, such a square root is mathematically problematic for the resulting theory, making it unfeasible.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Dirac's first insight was the concept of linearization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] By squaring this operator and demanding that it reduces to the Klein–Gordon equation, Dirac found that the variables must satisfy $\alpha _{i}^{2}=1$ and $\alpha _{i}\alpha _{j}+\alpha _{j}\alpha _{i}=0$ if $i\neq j$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Dirac initially considered the $2\times 2$ Pauli matrices as a candidate, but then showed these would not work since it is impossible to find a set of four $2\times 2$ matrices that all anticommute with each other.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] His second insight was to instead consider four-dimensional matrices.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In that case the equation would be acting on a four-component wavefunction $\psi =(\psi _{1},\psi _{2},\psi _{3},\psi _{4})$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Such a proposal was much more bold than Pauli's original generalization to a two-component wavefunction in the Pauli equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This is because in Pauli's case, this was motivated by the demand to encode the two spin states of the particle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In contrast, Dirac had no physical argument for a four-component wavefunction, but instead introduced it as a matter of mathematical necessity.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Dirac constructed the correct matrices $\alpha _{i}$ without realizing that they form a mathematical structure known of since the early 1880s, the Clifford algebra.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] By recasting the equation in a Lorentz invariant form, he also showed that it correctly combines special relativity with his principle of quantum mechanical transformation theory, making it a viable candidate for a relativistic theory of the electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] To investigate the equation further, he examined how it behaves in the presence of an electromagnetic field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] To his surprise, this showed that it described a particle with a magnetic moment arising due to the particle having spin ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Spin directly emerged from the equation, without Dirac having added it in by hand.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Additionally, he focused on showing that the equation successfully reproduces the fine structure of the hydrogen atom, at least to first order.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The equation therefore succeeds where all previous attempts have failed, in correctly describing relativistic phenomena of electrons from first principles rather than through the ad hoc modification of existing formulas.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Except for his followup paper deriving the Zeeman effect and Paschen–Back effect from the equation in the presences of a magnetic fields, Dirac left the work of examining the consequences of his equation to others, and only came back to the subject in 1930.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Once the equation was published, it was recognized as the correct solution to the problem of spin, relativity, and quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] At first the Dirac equation was considered the only valid relativistic equation for a particle with mass.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Then in 1934 Pauli and Victor Weisskopf reinterpreted the Klein–Gordon equation as the equation for a relativistic spinless particle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] One of the first calculations was to reproduce the Sommerfeld fine structure formula exactly, which was performed independently by Charles Galton Darwin and Walter Gordon in 1928.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This is the first time that the full formula has been derived from first principles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Further work on the mathematics of the equation was undertaken by Hermann Weyl in 1929.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In this work he showed that the massless Dirac equation can be decomposed into a pair of Weyl equations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac equation was also used to study various scattering processes.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In particular, the Klein–Nishina formula, looking at photon-electron scattering, was also derived in 1928.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Mott scattering, the scattering of electrons off a heavy target such as atomic nuclei, followed the next year.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Over the following years it was further used to derive other standard scattering processes such as Moller scattering in 1932 and Bhabha scattering in 1936.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] A problem that gained more focus with time was the presence of negative energy states in the Dirac equation, which led to many efforts to try to eliminate such states.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Dirac initially simply rejected the negative energy states as unphysical, but the problem was made more clear when in 1929 Oskar Klein showed that in static fields there exists inevitable mixing between the negative and positive energy states.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Dirac's initial response was to believe that his equation must have some sort of defect, and that it was only the first approximation of a future theory that would not have this problem.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] However, he then suggested a solution to the problem in the form of the Dirac sea.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This is the idea that the universe is filled with an infinite sea of negative energy electrons states.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Positive energy electron states then live in this sea and are prevented from decaying to the negative energy states through the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Additionally, Dirac postulated the existence of positively charged holes in the Dirac sea, which he initially suggested could be the proton.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] However, Oppenheimer showed that in this case stable atoms could not exist and Weyl further showed that the holes would have to have the same mass as the electrons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In 1933 Carl Anderson discovered the "positive electron", now called a positron, which had all the properties of Dirac's anti-electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] While the Dirac sea was later superseded by quantum field theory, its conceptual legacy survived in the idea of a dynamical vacuum filled with virtual particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In 1949 Ernst Stueckelberg suggested and Richard Feynman showed in detail that the negative energy solutions can be interpreted as particles traveling backwards in proper time.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The concept of the Dirac sea is also realized more explicitly in some condensed matter systems in the form of the Fermi sea, which consists of a sea of filled valence electrons below some chemical potential.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Significant work was done over the following decades to try to find spectroscopic discrepancies compared to the predictions made by the Dirac equation, however it was not until 1947 that Lamb shift was discovered, which the equation does not predict.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This led to the development of quantum electrodynamics in 1950s, with the Dirac equation then being incorporated within the context of quantum field theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Since it describes the dynamics of Dirac spinors, it went on to play a fundamental role in the Standard Model as well as many other areas of physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] For example, within condensed matter physics, systems whose fermions have a near linear dispersion relation are described by the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Such systems are known as Dirac matter and they include graphene and topological insulators, which have become a major area of research since the start of the 21st century.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac equation is inscribed upon a plaque on the floor of Westminster Abbey.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Unveiled on 13 November 1995, the plaque commemorates Dirac's life.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The equation, in its natural units formulation, is also prominently displayed in the auditorium at the ‘Paul A.M.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Blackett Institute (formerly The San Domenico Monastery) of the Ettore Majorana Foundation and Centre for Scientific Culture in Erice, Sicily.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In its modern field theoretic formulation, the Dirac equation in 3+1 dimensional Minkowski spacetime is written in terms of a *Dirac field* $\psi (x)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This is a field that assigns a complex vector from $\mathbb {C} ^{4}$ to each point in spacetime, where the key property of the field is that it transforms as a Dirac spinor under Lorentz transformations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where ${{\partial }\!\!\!/}=\gamma ^{\mu }\partial _{\mu }$ is a contraction between the four-gradient $\partial _{\mu }$ and the gamma matrices $\gamma ^{\mu }$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $\{a,b\}=ab+ba$ is the anticommutator, $\eta ^{\mu \nu }$ is the Minkowski metric in a mainly negative signature, and $I_{4}$ is the $4\times 4$ identity matrix.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac algebra is a special case of the more general mathematical structure known as a Clifford algebra.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac algebra can also be seen as the real part of the spacetime algebra.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] There is no unique choice of matrices for the gamma matrices, with different choices known as different representations of the algebra.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] One common choice, originally discovered by Dirac, is known as the Dirac representation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $\sigma _{i}$ are the three Pauli matrices for $i\in \{1,2,3\}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] There are two other common representations for the gamma matrices.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The first is the chiral representation, which is useful when decomposing the Dirac equation into a pair of Weyl equations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The second is the Majorana representation, for which all gamma matrices are imaginary, so the Dirac operator is purely real.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This representation is useful for studying Majorana spinors, which are purely real four-component spinor solutions of the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] By taking the hermitian conjugate of the Dirac equation and multiplying it by $\gamma ^{0}$ from the right, the adjoint Dirac equation can be found, with this being the equation of motion for the Dirac adjoint ${\bar {\psi }}=\psi ^{\dagger }\gamma ^{0}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The adjoint spinor is useful in forming Lorentz invariant quantities.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] For example, the bilinear $\psi ^{\dagger }\psi$ is not Lorentz invariant, but ${\bar {\psi }}\psi$ is.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Here ${\overleftarrow {\partial }}_{\mu }$ is shorthand notation for a partial derivative acting on the left.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The right-hand side of the equation is the Hamiltonian acting on the Dirac spinor $H\psi$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Here ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ and $\beta$ are a set of four Hermitian $4\times 4$ matrices that all anticommute with each other and square to the identity.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] They are related to the gamma matrices through $\gamma ^{0}=\beta$ and $\gamma ^{i}=\beta \alpha _{i}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This form is useful in quantum mechanics, where the Hamiltonian can be easily modified to solve a wide range of problems, such as by introducing a potential or through a minimal coupling to the electromagnetic field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The equation then arises as the Euler–Lagrange equation of this action, found by varying the adjoint spinor ${\bar {\psi }}(x)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Meanwhile, the adjoint Dirac equation is acquired by varying the spinor $\psi (x)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The action formulation of the Dirac equation has the advantage of making the symmetries of the Dirac equation more explicit, since they leave its action invariant.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Noether's theorem then allows for the direct calculation of currents corresponding to these symmetries.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Additionally, the action is usually used to define the associated quantum field theory, such as through the path integral formulation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In quantum mechanics, the Dirac spinor $\psi (x)$ corresponds to a four-component spinor wave function describing the state of a Dirac fermion.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Its position probability density, the probability of finding the fermion in a region of space, is described by the zeroth component of its vector current, $\psi ^{\dagger }\psi$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In the case of a large number of particles, it can also be interpreted as the charge density.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] An appropriate normalization is required to ensure that the total probability across all of space is equal to one, with probability conservation following directly from the conservation of the vector current.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac equation is the relativistic analogue of the Schrödinger equation for the Dirac fermion wavefunction.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In the second quantization form of quantum field theory the Dirac spinor is quantized to be an operator-valued spinor field ${\hat {\psi }}(x)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In contrast to quantum mechanics, it no longer represents the state in the Hilbert space, but is rather the operator that acts on states to create or destroy particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Observables are formed using expectation values of these operators.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In the path integral formulation of quantum field theory, the spinor field $\psi (x)$ is an anti-commuting Grassmann-valued field that only acts as an integration variable.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac equation then emerges as the classical saddle point behaviour of the path integral.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] in the sense of the Schwinger–Dyson equations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This version of the equation can also be acquired by taking the expectation value of the operator equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac equation also arises in describing the time evolution of a spinor field in classical field theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Such a field theory would have the special linear group ${\text{SL}}(2,\mathbb {C} )$ as its spacetime symmetry group rather than the Lorentz group, since the latter does not admit spinor representations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This is in contrast to the quantum theory which does admit spinor representations even when the spacetime symmetries are described by the Lorentz group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Classical spinor fields do not arise in our universe because the Pauli exclusion principle prevents populating the field with a sufficient number of particles to reach the classical limit.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Lorentz group ${\text{SO}}(1,3)$ , describing the transformation between inertial reference frames, can admit many different representations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] A representation is a particular choice of matrices that faithfully represent the action of the group on some vector space, where the dimensionality of the matrices can differ between representations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] For example, the Lorentz group can be represented by $4\times 4$ real matrices $\Lambda$ acting on the vector space $\mathbb {R} ^{1,3}$ , corresponding to how Lorentz transformations act on vectors or on spacetime.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Another representation is a set of $4\times 4$ complex matrices acting on Dirac spinors in the complex vector space $\mathbb {C} ^{4}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] A smaller representation is a set of $2\times 2$ complex matrices acting on Weyl spinors in the $\mathbb {C} ^{2}$ vector space.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Lie group elements can be generated using the corresponding Lie algebra, which together with a Lie bracket, describes the tangent space of the group manifold around its identity element.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The basis elements of this vector space are known as generators of the group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] A particular group element is then acquired by exponentiating a corresponding tangent space vector.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The generators of the Lorentz Lie algebra must satisfy certain anticommutation relations, known as a Lie bracket.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This algebra admits numerous representation, where each generator is represented by a matrix, with each algebra representation generating a corresponding representation of the group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $\omega _{\mu \nu }$ is an antisymmetric matrix encoding the six degrees of freedom of the Lorentz group used to specify the particular group element.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] These correspond to the three boosts and three rotations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The mapping of $\Lambda \mapsto S[\Lambda ]$ is not one-to-one since there are two consistent choices for $\omega _{\mu \nu }$ that give the same $\Lambda$ but a different $S[\Lambda ]$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This is a consequence of the spinor representation being projective representations of the Lorentz group ${\text{SO}}(1,3)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Equivalently, they are regular representation of ${\text{SL}}(2,\mathbb {C} )$ , which is a double cover of the Lorentz group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac equation is a Lorentz covariant equation, meaning that it takes the form in all inertial reference frames.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $\partial _{\mu }'$ is the four-gradient for the new coordinates $x'$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Meanwhile, the Dirac action is Lorentz invariant, meaning that it is the same in all reference frames $S'=S$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This symmetry is known as the vector symmetry because its current transforms as a vector under Lorentz transformations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Promoting this symmetry to a gauge symmetry gives rise to quantum electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $\gamma _{5}$ is the chiral matrix.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This arises because in the massless limit the Dirac equation reduces to a pair of Weyl equations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Each of these is invariant under a ${\text{U}}(1)$ phase symmetry.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] These two symmetries can then be grouped into the vector symmetry where both Weyl spinors transform by the same phase, and the axial symmetry where they transform under the opposite signs of the phase.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This transforms as a pseudovector, meaning that its spatial part is odd under parity transformations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Classically, the axial symmetry admits a well-formulated gauge theory, but at the quantum level it has a chiral anomaly that provides an obstruction towards gauging.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The spacetime symmetries of the Dirac action correspond to the Poincaré group, a combination of spacetime translations and the Lorentz group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where the last term is the Dirac Lagrangian, which vanishes on shell.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $S^{\rho \sigma }$ are the spinor representation generators of the Lorentz Lie algebra, used to define how spinors transform under Lorentz transformations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] As a result, any solution to the Dirac equation is also automatically a solution to the Klein–Gordon equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Its solutions can therefore be written as a linear combination of plane waves.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] It also admits negative frequency solutions taking the same form except with $p_{0}=-{\sqrt {{\boldsymbol {p}}^{2}+m^{2}}}<0$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Since these are simple matrix equations, they can be solved directly once an explicit representation for the gamma matrices is chosen.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $\xi _{s}$ and $\eta _{s}$ are arbitrary complex 2-vectors, describing the two spin degrees of freedom for the particle and two for the antiparticle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In the massless limit, these spin states correspond to the possible helicity states that the massless fermions can have, either being left-handed or right-handed.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] While the standard Dirac equation was originally derived in a $3+1$ dimensional spacetime, it can be directly generalized to arbitrary dimension and metric signatures, where it takes the same covariant form.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The crucial difference is that the gamma matrices must be changed to gamma matrices of the Clifford algebra appropriate in those dimensions and metric signature, with the size of the Dirac spinor corresponding to the dimensionality of the gamma matrices.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] While the Dirac equation always exists, since every dimension admits Dirac spinors, the properties of these spinors and their relation to other spinor representations differs significantly across dimensions.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Other differences include the absence of a chirality matrix in odd dimensions.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $\omega _{\alpha \beta }$ is the spin connection that can be defined using the tetrad formalism.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Adding self-interaction terms to the Dirac action gives rise to the nonlinear Dirac equation, which allows for the fermions to interact with themselves, such as in the Thirring model.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Interactions between fermions can also be introduced through electromagnetic effects.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In particular, the Breit equation describes multi-electron systems interacting electromagnetically to first order in perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The two-body Dirac equation is a similar multi-body equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] A geometric reformulation of the Dirac equation is known as the Dirac–Hestenes equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In this formulation all the components of the Dirac equation have an explicit geometric interpretation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Another related geometric equation is the Dirac–Kähler equation, which is a geometric analogue of the Dirac equation that can be defined on any general pseudo-Riemannian manifold and which acts on differential forms.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In the case of a flat manifold, it reduces to four copies of the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] However, on curved manifolds this decomposition breaks down and the equation fundamentally differs.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This equation is used in lattice field theory to describe the continuum limit of staggered fermions.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Dirac spinor can be decomposed into a pair of Weyl spinors of opposite chirality $\psi ^{T}=(\psi _{L},\psi _{R})$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Under Lorentz transformations, one transforms as a left-handed Weyl spinor $\psi _{L}$ and the other as a right-handed Weyl spinor $\psi _{R}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In particular, in the massless limit the Weyl spinors decouple and the Dirac equation is equivalent to a pair of Weyl equations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This decomposition has been proposed as an intuitive explanation of Zitterbewegung, as these massless components would propagate at the speed of light and move in opposite directions, since the helicity is the projection of the spin onto the direction of motion.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Here the role of the mass is not to make the velocity less than the speed of light, but instead controls the average rate at which these reversals occur; specifically, the reversals can be modelled as a Poisson process.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] A closely related equation is the Majorana equation, with this formally taking the same form as the Dirac equation except that it acts on Majorana spinors.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] These are spinors that satisfy a reality condition $\psi =C{\bar {\psi }}^{T}$ , where C is the charge-conjugation operator.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In higher dimensions, the Dirac equation has similar relations to the equations describing other spinor representations that arise in those dimensions.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Here ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}$ is the vector of Pauli matrices and ${\hat {\boldsymbol {p}}}=-i\nabla$ is the momentum operator.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The equation describes a fermion of charge q coupled to the electromagnetic field through a magnetic vector potential ${\boldsymbol {A}}$ and an electric scalar potential $\phi$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The fermion is described through the two-component wave function $|\psi \rangle$ , where each component describes one of the two spin states $|\psi \rangle =\psi _{+}|\uparrow \rangle +\psi _{-}|\downarrow \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The Pauli equation is often used in quantum mechanics to describe phenomena where relativistic effects are negligible but the spin of the fermion is important.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] It can also be recast in a form which directly shows that the gyromagnetic ratio of the fermion described by the Dirac equation is exactly $g=2$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In quantum electrodynamics there are additional quantum corrections that modify this value, give rise to a non-zero anomalous magnetic moment.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The vector and axial symmetries of the Dirac action are both global symmetries, in that they act the same everywhere in spacetime.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In classical field theory, the Lagrangian can always be modified in a way to elevate a global symmetry to a local symmetry, which can act differently at different spacetime locations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] For example, the axial symmetry in the massless Dirac theory with one fermion is anomalous due to the chiral anomaly and cannot be gauged.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Elevating the vector symmetry to a local symmetry means that the original action is no longer invariant under the symmetry due to the appearance of a $\partial _{\mu }\alpha (x)$ term arising from the kinetic term.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Instead, a new field $A_{\mu }(x)$ , known as a gauge field, must be introduced.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where e plays the role of the charge of the Dirac spinor to the gauge field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] This result can also be directly acquired through the Noether procedure, which is the general principle that a global symmetry can be gauged through the introduction of a term coupling the gauge field to the appropriate global symmetry current.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Additionally introducing the kinetic term for the gauge field results in the action for quantum electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The symmetries that can be gauged can be greatly expanded by considering a theory with N identical Dirac spinors $\psi ^{a}$ labelled by a new index a .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Together these spinors can be considered as being part of a single object $\psi$ with components $\psi ^{i,a}$ where i labels the four spin components, and a the different spinors.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The largest global symmetry of this action is then given by the unitary group ${\text{U}}(N)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Any continuous subgroup of ${\text{U}}(N)$ can then be gauged.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] In particular, if one wishes to gauge the symmetry acting on all N components, then the symmetry being gauged must admit an N -dimensional unitary representation acting on the spinors.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] forms a faithful representation of the group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Gauging the largest continuous subgroup, ${\text{SU}}(N)$ , requires the spinors to transform in the fundamental or antifundamental representation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] Gauging elevates the representation from being spacetime independent to being spacetime dependent $\rho (g(x))$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] It requires introducing a gauge field $A_{\mu }^{a}$ , formally the connection on the principal bundle, which necessarily transforms in the adjoint representation of the gauge group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] One symmetry that frequently gets gauged is the special unitary group ${\text{SU}}(N)$ symmetry.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] where $U(x)$ is a $N\times N$ unitary matrix corresponding to a particular group element.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The case of ${\text{SU}}(3)$ describes strong interactions of the quark sector of the Standard Model, with the gauge field corresponding to gluons and the Dirac spinors to the quarks.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The ${\text{SU}}(2)$ case also plays a role in the Standard Model, describing the electroweak sector.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/dirac-equation] The gauge field in this case is the W-boson, while the Dirac spinors are leptons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A **photon** (from Ancient Greek φῶς*,*φωτός*(*phôs, phōtós*)* 'light') is an elementary particle that is a quantum of the electromagnetic field, including electromagnetic radiation such as light and radio waves, and the force carrier for the electromagnetic force.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Photons are massless particles that can only move at one speed, the speed of light measured in a vacuum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The photon belongs to the class of boson particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] As with other elementary particles, photons are best explained by quantum mechanics and exhibit wave–particle duality, their behavior featuring properties of both waves and particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The modern photon concept originated during the first two decades of the 20th century with the work of Albert Einstein, who built upon the research of Max Planck.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] While Planck was trying to explain how matter and electromagnetic radiation could be in thermal equilibrium with one another, he proposed that the energy stored within a material object should be regarded as composed of an integer number of discrete, equal-sized parts.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] To explain the photoelectric effect, Einstein introduced the idea that light itself is made of discrete units of energy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Lewis popularized the term *photon* for these energy units.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Subsequently, many other experiments validated Einstein's approach.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In the Standard Model of particle physics, photons and other elementary particles are described as a necessary consequence of physical laws having a certain symmetry at every point in spacetime.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The intrinsic properties of particles, such as charge, mass, and spin, are determined by gauge symmetry.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The photon concept has led to momentous advances in experimental and theoretical physics, including lasers, Bose–Einstein condensation, quantum field theory, and the probabilistic interpretation of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] It has been applied to photochemistry, high-resolution microscopy, and measurements of molecular distances.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Moreover, photons have been studied as elements of quantum computers, and for applications in optical imaging and optical communication such as quantum cryptography.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The photon has no electric charge, is generally considered to have zero rest mass, and is a stable particle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The experimental upper limit on the photon mass is very small, on the order of 10−53 g; its lifetime would be more than 1018 years.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For comparison, the age of the universe is about 1.38×1010 years.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Single photons have been shown to travel at the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The measurement uses a heralded single photon source.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In a vacuum, a photon has two possible polarization states.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The photon is the gauge boson for electromagnetism, and therefore all other quantum numbers of the photon (such as lepton number, baryon number, and flavour quantum numbers) are zero.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Also, photons obey Bose–Einstein statistics, and not Fermi–Dirac statistics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] That is, they do *not* obey the Pauli exclusion principle, and more than one photon can occupy the same bound quantum state.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Photons are emitted when a charge is accelerated and emits synchrotron radiation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] During a molecular, atomic, or nuclear transition to a lower energy level, the photons emitted have characteristic energies ranging from radio waves to gamma rays.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Photons can also be emitted when a particle and its corresponding antiparticle are annihilated (for example, electron–positron annihilation).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] where h is the Planck constant, a fundamental physical constant.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] where *ħ* ≡ ⁠*h*/ 2*π* ⁠ is called the reduced Planck constant and c is the speed of light.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The photon energy can be written as *E* = *pc* where p is the magnitude of the momentum vector ***p***.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The photon also carries spin angular momentum, which is related to photon polarization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] (Beams of light also exhibit properties described as orbital angular momentum of light).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The angular momentum of the photon has two possible values, either +ħ or −ħ.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] These two possible values correspond to the two possible pure states of circular polarization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Collections of photons in a light beam may have mixtures of these two values; a linearly polarized light beam will act as if it were composed of equal numbers of the two possible angular momenta.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The spin angular momentum of light does not depend on its frequency, and was experimentally verified by C.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The collision of a particle with its antiparticle can create photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In free space at least *two* photons must be created since, in the center of momentum frame, the colliding antiparticles have no net momentum, whereas a single photon always has momentum (determined by the photon's frequency or wavelength, which cannot be zero).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Hence, conservation of momentum (or equivalently, translational invariance) requires that at least two photons are created, with zero net momentum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The energy of the two photons, or, equivalently, their frequency, may be determined from conservation of four-momentum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Seen another way, the photon can be considered as its own antiparticle (thus an "antiphoton" is simply a normal photon with opposite momentum, equal polarization, and 180° out of phase).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The reverse process, pair production, is the dominant mechanism by which high-energy photons such as gamma rays lose energy while passing through matter.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] That process is the reverse of "annihilation to one photon" allowed in the electric field of an atomic nucleus.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The classical formulae for the energy and momentum of electromagnetic radiation can be re-expressed in terms of photon events.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For example, the pressure of electromagnetic radiation on an object derives from the transfer of photon momentum per unit time and unit area to that object, since pressure is force per unit area and force is the change in momentum per unit time.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Current commonly accepted physical theories imply or assume the photon to be strictly massless.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] If photons were not purely massless, their speeds would vary with frequency, with lower-energy (redder) photons moving slightly slower than higher-energy photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Relativity would be unaffected by this; the so-called speed of light, *c*, would then not be the actual speed at which light moves, but a constant of nature which is the upper bound on speed that any object could theoretically attain in spacetime.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Thus, it would still be the speed of spacetime ripples (gravitational waves and gravitons), but it would not be the speed of photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] If a photon did have non-zero mass, there would be other effects as well.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Coulomb's law would be modified and the electromagnetic field would have an extra physical degree of freedom.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] These effects yield more sensitive experimental probes of the photon mass than the frequency dependence of the speed of light.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] If Coulomb's law is not exactly valid, then that would allow the presence of an electric field to exist within a hollow conductor when it is subjected to an external electric field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This provides a means for precision tests of Coulomb's law.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A null result of such an experiment has set a limit of *m* ≲ 10−14 eV/*c*2.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Sharper upper limits on the mass of light have been obtained in experiments designed to detect effects caused by the galactic vector potential.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Although the galactic vector potential is large because the galactic magnetic field exists on great length scales, only the magnetic field would be observable if the photon is massless.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In the case that the photon has mass, the mass term ⁠1/2⁠*m*2*A**μ**A**μ* would affect the galactic plasma.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The fact that no such effects are seen implies an upper bound on the photon mass of *m* < 3×10−27 eV/*c*2.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The galactic vector potential can also be probed directly by measuring the torque exerted on a magnetized ring.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Such methods were used to obtain the sharper upper limit of 1.07×10−27 eV/*c*2 (10−36 Da) given by the Particle Data Group.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] These sharp limits from the non-observation of the effects caused by the galactic vector potential have been shown to be model-dependent.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] If the photon mass is generated via the Higgs mechanism then the upper limit of *m* ≲ 10−14 eV/*c*2 from the test of Coulomb's law is valid.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In most theories up to the eighteenth century, light was pictured as being made of particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In the early 19th century, Thomas Young and August Fresnel clearly demonstrated the interference and diffraction of light, and by 1850 wave models were generally accepted.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] James Clerk Maxwell's 1865 prediction that light was an electromagnetic wave – which was confirmed experimentally in 1888 by Heinrich Hertz's detection of radio waves – seemed to be the final blow to particle models of light.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The Maxwell wave theory, however, does not account for *all* properties of light.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The Maxwell theory predicts that the energy of a light wave depends only on its intensity, not on its frequency; nevertheless, several independent types of experiments show that the energy imparted by light to atoms depends only on the light's frequency, not on its intensity.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For example, some chemical reactions are provoked only by light of frequency higher than a certain threshold; light of frequency lower than the threshold, no matter how intense, does not initiate the reaction.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Similarly, electrons can be ejected from a metal plate by shining light of sufficiently high frequency on it (the photoelectric effect); the energy of the ejected electron is related only to the light's frequency, not to its intensity.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] As shown by Albert Einstein, some form of energy quantization *must* be assumed to account for the thermal equilibrium observed between matter and electromagnetic radiation; for this explanation of the photoelectric effect, Einstein received the 1921 Nobel Prize in physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Since the Maxwell theory of light allows for all possible energies of electromagnetic radiation, most physicists assumed initially that the energy quantization resulted from some unknown constraint on the matter that absorbs or emits the radiation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1905, Einstein was the first to propose that energy quantization was a property of electromagnetic radiation itself.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1909 and 1916, Einstein showed that, if Planck's law regarding black-body radiation is accepted, the energy quanta must also carry momentum p = ⁠ h / λ ⁠ , making them full-fledged particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] As recounted in Robert Millikan's 1923 Nobel lecture, Einstein's 1905 predicted energy relationship was verified experimentally by 1916 but the local concept of the quanta remained unsettled.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Most physicists were reluctant to believe that electromagnetic radiation itself might be particulate and thus an example of wave-particle duality.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Then in 1922 the Arthur Compton experiment showed that photons carried momentum proportional to their wave number (and therefore energy) in an effect now called Compton scattering that appeared to clearly support a localized quantum model.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] At least for Millikan, this settled the matter.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Compton received the Nobel Prize in 1927 for his scattering work.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Even after Compton's experiment, Niels Bohr, Hendrik Kramers and John Slater made one last attempt to preserve the Maxwellian continuous electromagnetic field model of light, the so-called BKS theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] An important feature of the BKS theory is how it treated the conservation of energy and the conservation of momentum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In the BKS theory, energy and momentum are only conserved on the average across many interactions between matter and radiation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, refined Compton experiments showed that the conservation laws hold for individual interactions.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Accordingly, Bohr and his co-workers gave their model "as honorable a funeral as possible".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Nevertheless, the failures of the BKS model inspired Werner Heisenberg in his development of matrix mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] By the late 1920, the pivotal question was how to unify Maxwell's wave theory of light with its experimentally observed particle nature.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The answer to this question occupied Albert Einstein for the rest of his life, and was solved in quantum electrodynamics and its successor, the Standard Model.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A few physicists persisted in developing semiclassical models in which electromagnetic radiation is not quantized, but matter appears to obey the laws of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In the 1970s and 1980s photon-correlation experiments definitively demonstrated quantum photon effects.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] These experiments produce results that cannot be explained by any classical theory of light, since they involve anticorrelations that result from the quantum measurement process.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1974, the first such experiment was carried out by Clauser, who reported a violation of a classical Cauchy–Schwarz inequality.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The word *quanta* (singular *quantum,* Latin for *how much*) was used before 1900 to mean particles or amounts of different quantities, including electricity.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1905, Albert Einstein published a paper in which he proposed that many light-related phenomena—including black-body radiation and the photoelectric effect—would be better explained by modelling electromagnetic waves as consisting of spatially localized, discrete energy quanta.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] He called these *a light quantum* (German: *ein Lichtquant*).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The name *photon* derives from the Greek word for light, *φῶς* (transliterated *phôs*).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The name was used 1916 by the American physicist and psychologist Leonard T.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Troland for a unit of illumination of the retina and in several other contexts before being adopted for physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The use of the term *photon* for the light quantum was popularized by Gilbert N.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Lewis, who used the term in a letter to *Nature* on 18 December 1926.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Arthur Compton, who had performed a key experiment demonstrating light quanta, cited Lewis in the 1927 Solvay conference proceedings for suggesting the name *photon*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In physics, a photon is usually denoted by the symbol γ (the Greek letter gamma).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This symbol for the photon probably derives from gamma rays, which were discovered in 1900 by Paul Villard, named by Ernest Rutherford in 1903, and shown to be a form of electromagnetic radiation in 1914 by Rutherford and Edward Andrade.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In chemistry and optical engineering, photons are usually symbolized by hν, which is the photon energy, where h is the Planck constant and the Greek letter ν (nu) is the photon's frequency.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Photons obey the laws of quantum mechanics, and so their behavior has both wave-like and particle-like aspects.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] When a photon is detected by a measuring instrument, it is registered as a single, particulate unit.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, the *probability* of detecting a photon is calculated by equations that describe waves.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This combination of aspects is known as wave–particle duality.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For example, the probability distribution for the location at which a photon might be detected displays clearly wave-like phenomena such as diffraction and interference.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A single photon passing through a double slit has its energy received at a point on the screen with a probability distribution given by its interference pattern determined by Maxwell's wave equations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, experiments confirm that the photon is *not* a short pulse of electromagnetic radiation; a photon's Maxwell waves will diffract, but photon energy does not spread out as it propagates, nor does this energy divide when it encounters a beam splitter.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Rather, the received photon acts like a point-like particle since it is absorbed or emitted *as a whole* by arbitrarily small systems, including systems much smaller than its wavelength, such as an atomic nucleus (≈10−15 m across) or even the point-like electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] While many introductory texts treat photons using the mathematical techniques of non-relativistic quantum mechanics, this is in some ways an awkward oversimplification, as photons are by nature intrinsically relativistic.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Because photons have zero rest mass, no wave function defined for a photon can have all the properties familiar from wave functions in non-relativistic quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In order to avoid these difficulties, physicists employ the second-quantized theory of photons described below, quantum electrodynamics, in which photons are quantized excitations of electromagnetic modes.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Another difficulty is finding the proper analogue for the uncertainty principle, an idea frequently attributed to Heisenberg, who introduced the concept in analyzing a thought experiment involving an electron and a high-energy photon.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, Heisenberg did not give precise mathematical definitions of what the "uncertainty" in these measurements meant.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The precise mathematical statement of the position–momentum uncertainty principle is due to Kennard, Pauli, and Weyl.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The uncertainty principle applies to situations where an experimenter has a choice of measuring either one of two "canonically conjugate" quantities, like the position and the momentum of a particle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A coherent state minimizes the overall uncertainty as far as quantum mechanics allows.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Quantum optics makes use of coherent states for modes of the electromagnetic field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] There is a tradeoff, reminiscent of the position–momentum uncertainty relation, between measurements of an electromagnetic wave's amplitude and its phase.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This is sometimes informally expressed in terms of the uncertainty in the number of photons present in the electromagnetic wave, $\Delta N$ , and the uncertainty in the phase of the wave, $\Delta \phi$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, this cannot be an uncertainty relation of the Kennard–Pauli–Weyl type, since unlike position and momentum, the phase $\phi$ cannot be represented by a Hermitian operator.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1924, Satyendra Nath Bose derived Planck's law of black-body radiation without using any electromagnetism, but rather by using a modification of coarse-grained counting of phase space.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Einstein showed that this modification is equivalent to assuming that photons are rigorously identical and that it implied a "mysterious non-local interaction", now understood as the requirement for a symmetric quantum mechanical state.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This work led to the concept of coherent states and the development of the laser.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In the same papers, Einstein extended Bose's formalism to material particles (bosons) and predicted that they would condense into their lowest quantum state at low enough temperatures; this Bose–Einstein condensation was observed experimentally in 1995.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] It was later used by Lene Hau to slow, and then completely stop, light in 1999 and 2001.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The modern view on this is that photons are, by virtue of their integer spin, bosons (as opposed to fermions with half-integer spin).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] By the spin-statistics theorem, all bosons obey Bose–Einstein statistics (whereas all fermions obey Fermi–Dirac statistics).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1916, Albert Einstein showed that Planck's radiation law could be derived from a semi-classical, statistical treatment of photons and atoms, which implies a link between the rates at which atoms emit and absorb photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The condition follows from the assumption that functions of the emission and absorption of radiation by the atoms are independent of each other, and that thermal equilibrium is made by way of the radiation's interaction with the atoms.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Consider a cavity in thermal equilibrium with all parts of itself and filled with electromagnetic radiation and that the atoms can emit and absorb that radiation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Einstein began by postulating simple proportionality relations for the different reaction rates involved.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] where $B_{ji}$ is the rate constant for absorption.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For the reverse process, there are two possibilities: spontaneous emission of a photon, or the emission of a photon initiated by the interaction of the atom with a passing photon and the return of the atom to the lower-energy state.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] where $A_{ij}$ is the rate constant for emitting a photon spontaneously, and $B_{ij}$ is the rate constant for emissions in response to ambient photons (induced or stimulated emission).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In thermodynamic equilibrium, the number of atoms in state i and those in state j must, on average, be constant; hence, the rates $R_{ji}$ and $R_{ij}$ must be equal.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The $A_{ij}$ and $B_{ij}$ are collectively known as the *Einstein coefficients*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Einstein could not fully justify his rate equations, but claimed that it should be possible to calculate the coefficients $A_{ij}$ , $B_{ji}$ and $B_{ij}$ once physicists had obtained "mechanics and electrodynamics modified to accommodate the quantum hypothesis".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Not long thereafter, in 1926, Paul Dirac derived the $B_{ij}$ rate constants by using a semiclassical approach, and, in 1927, succeeded in deriving *all* the rate constants from first principles within the framework of quantum theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Dirac's work was the foundation of quantum electrodynamics, i.e., the quantization of the electromagnetic field itself.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Dirac's approach is also called *second quantization* or quantum field theory; earlier quantum mechanical treatments only treat material particles as quantum mechanical, not the electromagnetic field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Einstein was troubled by the fact that his theory seemed incomplete, since it did not determine the *direction* of a spontaneously emitted photon.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A probabilistic nature of light-particle motion was first considered by Newton in his treatment of birefringence and, more generally, of the splitting of light beams at interfaces into a transmitted beam and a reflected beam.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Newton hypothesized that hidden variables in the light particle determined which of the two paths a single photon would take.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Similarly, Einstein hoped for a more complete theory that would leave nothing to chance, beginning his separation from quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Ironically, Max Born's probabilistic interpretation of the wave function was inspired by Einstein's later work searching for a more complete theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1910, Peter Debye derived Planck's law of black-body radiation from a relatively simple assumption.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] He decomposed the electromagnetic field in a cavity into its Fourier modes, and assumed that the energy in any mode was an integer multiple of $h\nu$ , where $\nu$ is the frequency of the electromagnetic mode.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Planck's law of black-body radiation follows immediately as a geometric sum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, Debye's approach failed to give the correct formula for the energy fluctuations of black-body radiation, which were derived by Einstein in 1909.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 1925, Born, Heisenberg and Jordan reinterpreted Debye's concept in a key way.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] As may be shown classically, the Fourier modes of the electromagnetic field—a complete set of electromagnetic plane waves indexed by their wave vector ***k*** and polarization state—are equivalent to a set of uncoupled simple harmonic oscillators.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Treated quantum mechanically, the energy levels of such oscillators are known to be $E=nh\nu$ , where $\nu$ is the oscillator frequency.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The key new step was to identify an electromagnetic mode with energy $E=nh\nu$ as a state with n photons, each of energy $h\nu$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This approach gives the correct energy fluctuation formula.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] He treated the interaction between a charge and an electromagnetic field as a small perturbation that induces transitions in the photon states, changing the numbers of photons in the modes, while conserving energy and momentum overall.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In Dirac's time, it was not yet known that all bosons, including photons, must obey Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Dirac's second-order perturbation theory can involve virtual photons, transient intermediate states of the electromagnetic field; the static electric and magnetic interactions are mediated by such virtual photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Although these transient virtual photons can never be observed, they contribute measurably to the probabilities of observable events.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Second-order and higher-order perturbation calculations can give infinite contributions to the sum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Such unphysical results are corrected for using the technique of renormalization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Other virtual particles may contribute to the summation as well; for example, two photons may interact indirectly through virtual electron–positron pairs.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Such photon–photon scattering (see two-photon physics), as well as electron–photon scattering, is meant to be one of the modes of operations of the planned particle accelerator, the International Linear Collider.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] where $|n_{k_{i}}\rangle$ represents the state in which $\,n_{k_{i}}$ photons are in the mode $k_{i}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In this notation, the creation of a new photon in mode $k_{i}$ (e.g., emitted from an atomic transition) is written as $|n_{k_{i}}\rangle \rightarrow |n_{k_{i}}+1\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This notation merely expresses the concept of Born, Heisenberg and Jordan described above, and does not add any physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The electromagnetic field can be understood as a gauge field, i.e., as a field that results from requiring that a gauge symmetry holds independently at every position in spacetime.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For the electromagnetic field, this gauge symmetry is the Abelian U(1) symmetry of complex numbers of absolute value 1, which reflects the ability to vary the phase of a complex field without affecting observables or real valued functions made from it, such as the energy or the Lagrangian.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The quanta of an Abelian gauge field must be massless, uncharged bosons, as long as the symmetry is not broken; hence, the photon is predicted to be massless, and to have zero electric charge and integer spin.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The particular form of the electromagnetic interaction specifies that the photon must have spin ±1; thus, its helicity must be $\pm \hbar$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] These two spin components correspond to the classical concepts of right-handed and left-handed circularly polarized light.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, the transient virtual photons of quantum electrodynamics may also adopt unphysical polarization states.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In the prevailing Standard Model of physics, the photon is one of four gauge bosons in the electroweak interaction; the other three are denoted W+, W− and Z0 and are responsible for the weak interaction.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Unlike the photon, these gauge bosons have mass, owing to a mechanism that breaks their SU(2) gauge symmetry.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The unification of the photon with W and Z gauge bosons in the electroweak interaction was accomplished by Sheldon Glashow, Abdus Salam and Steven Weinberg, for which they were awarded the 1979 Nobel Prize in physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Physicists continue to hypothesize grand unified theories that connect these four gauge bosons with the eight gluon gauge bosons of quantum chromodynamics; however, key predictions of these theories, such as proton decay, have not been observed experimentally.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Measurements of the interaction between energetic photons and hadrons show that the interaction is much more intense than expected by the interaction of merely photons with the hadron's electric charge.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Furthermore, the interaction of energetic photons with protons is similar to the interaction of photons with neutrons in spite of the fact that the electrical charge structures of protons and neutrons are substantially different.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A theory called vector meson dominance (VMD) was developed to explain this effect.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] According to VMD, the photon is a superposition of the pure electromagnetic photon, which interacts only with electric charges, and vector mesons, which mediate the residual nuclear force.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, if experimentally probed at very short distances, the intrinsic structure of the photon appears to have as components a charge-neutral flux of quarks and gluons, quasi-free according to asymptotic freedom in QCD.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] That flux is described by the *photon structure function*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A review by Nisius (2000) presented a comprehensive comparison of data with theoretical predictions.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The energy of a system that emits a photon is *decreased* by the energy E of the photon as measured in the rest frame of the emitting system, which may result in a reduction in mass in the amount ${E}/{c^{2}}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Similarly, the mass of a system that absorbs a photon is *increased* by a corresponding amount.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] As an application, the energy balance of nuclear reactions involving photons is commonly written in terms of the masses of the nuclei involved, and terms of the form ${E}/{c^{2}}$ for the gamma photons (and for other relevant energies, such as the recoil energy of nuclei).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This concept is applied in key predictions of quantum electrodynamics (QED, see above).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In that theory, the mass of electrons (or, more generally, leptons) is modified by including the mass contributions of virtual photons, in a technique known as renormalization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Such "radiative corrections" contribute to a number of predictions of QED, such as the magnetic dipole moment of leptons, the Lamb shift, and the hyperfine structure of bound lepton pairs, such as muonium and positronium.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Since photons contribute to the stress–energy tensor, they exert a gravitational attraction on other objects, according to the theory of general relativity.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Conversely, photons are themselves affected by gravity; their normally straight trajectories may be bent by warped spacetime, as in gravitational lensing, and their frequencies may be lowered by moving to a higher gravitational potential, as in the Pound–Rebka experiment.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, these effects are not specific to photons; exactly the same effects would be predicted for classical electromagnetic waves.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Light that travels through transparent matter does so at a lower speed than *c*, the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The factor by which the speed is decreased is called the refractive index of the material.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In a classical wave picture, the slowing can be explained by the light inducing electric polarization in the matter, the polarized matter radiating new light, and that new light interfering with the original light wave to form a delayed wave.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In a particle picture, the slowing can instead be described as a blending of the photon with quantum excitations of the matter to produce quasi-particles known as polaritons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Polaritons have a nonzero effective mass, which means that they cannot travel at *c*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Light of different frequencies may travel through matter at different speeds; this is called dispersion (not to be confused with scattering).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In some cases, it can result in extremely slow speeds of light in matter.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The effects of photon interactions with other quasi-particles may be observed directly in Raman scattering and Brillouin scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For example, photons scatter so many times in the solar radiative zone after leaving the core of the Sun that radiant energy takes about a million years to reach the convection zone.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, photons emitted from the sun's photosphere take only 8.3 minutes to reach Earth.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Photons can also be absorbed by nuclei, atoms or molecules, provoking transitions between their energy levels.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] A classic example is the molecular transition of retinal (C20H28O), which is responsible for vision, as discovered in 1958 by Nobel laureate biochemist George Wald and co-workers.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The absorption provokes a cis–trans isomerization that, in combination with other such transitions, is transduced into nerve impulses.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The absorption of photons can even break chemical bonds, as in the photodissociation of chlorine; this is the subject of photochemistry.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Photons have many applications in technology.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] These examples are chosen to illustrate applications of photons *per se*, rather than general optical devices such as lenses, etc. that could operate under a classical theory of light.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The laser is an important application and is discussed above under stimulated emission.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Individual photons can be detected by several methods.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The classic photomultiplier tube exploits the photoelectric effect: a photon of sufficient energy strikes a metal plate and knocks free an electron, initiating an ever-amplifying avalanche of electrons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Semiconductor charge-coupled device chips use a similar effect: an incident photon generates a charge on a microscopic capacitor that can be detected.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Other detectors such as Geiger counters use the ability of photons to ionize gas molecules contained in the device, causing a detectable change of conductivity of the gas.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Planck's energy formula $E=h\nu$ is often used by engineers and chemists in design, both to compute the change in energy resulting from a photon absorption and to determine the frequency of the light emitted from a given photon emission.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] For example, the emission spectrum of a gas-discharge lamp can be altered by filling it with (mixtures of) gases with different electronic energy level configurations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Under some conditions, an energy transition can be excited by "two" photons that individually would be insufficient.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This allows for higher resolution microscopy, because the sample absorbs energy only in the spectrum where two beams of different colors overlap significantly, which can be made much smaller than the excitation volume of a single beam (see two-photon excitation microscopy).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Moreover, these photons cause less damage to the sample, since they are of lower energy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In some cases, two energy transitions can be coupled so that, as one system absorbs a photon, another nearby system "steals" its energy and re-emits a photon of a different frequency.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] This is the basis of fluorescence resonance energy transfer, a technique that is used in molecular biology to study the interaction of suitable proteins.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Several different kinds of hardware random number generators involve the detection of single photons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In one example, for each bit in the random sequence that is to be produced, a photon is sent to a beam-splitter.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In such a situation, there are two possible outcomes of equal probability.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The actual outcome is used to determine whether the next bit in the sequence is 0 or 1.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Much research has been devoted to applications of photons in the field of quantum optics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Photons seem well-suited to be elements of an extremely fast quantum computer, and the quantum entanglement of photons is a focus of research.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Nonlinear optical processes are another active research area, with topics such as two-photon absorption, self-phase modulation, modulational instability and optical parametric oscillators.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] However, such processes generally do not require the assumption of photons *per se*; they may often be modeled by treating atoms as nonlinear oscillators.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] The nonlinear process of spontaneous parametric down conversion is often used to produce single-photon states.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Finally, photons are essential in some aspects of optical communication, especially for quantum cryptography.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] Two-photon physics studies interactions between photons, which are rare.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/photon] In 2018, Massachusetts Institute of Technology researchers announced the discovery of bound photon triplets, which may involve polaritons.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In particle physics, **quantum electrodynamics** (**QED**) is the relativistic quantum field theory of electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In essence, it describes how light and matter interact and is the first theory where full agreement between quantum mechanics and special relativity is achieved.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] QED mathematically describes all phenomena involving electrically charged particles interacting by means of exchange of photons and represents the quantum counterpart of classical electromagnetism giving a complete account of matter and light interaction.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In technical terms, QED can be described as a perturbation theory of the electromagnetic quantum vacuum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Richard Feynman called it "the jewel of physics" for its extremely accurate predictions of quantities like the anomalous magnetic moment of the electron and the Lamb shift of the energy levels of hydrogen.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] It is the most precise and stringently tested theory in physics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] However, the prediction of vacuum zero energy made by QED has 10^120 magnitude of difference compared to experimental observation value.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This is called cosmological constant problem or vacuum catastrophe.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The first formulation of a quantum theory describing radiation and matter interaction is attributed to Paul Dirac, who during the 1920s computed the coefficient of spontaneous emission of an atom.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] He is credited with coining the term "quantum electrodynamics".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Dirac described the quantization of the electromagnetic field as an ensemble of harmonic oscillators with the introduction of the concept of creation and annihilation operators of particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In the following years, with contributions from Wolfgang Pauli, Eugene Wigner, Pascual Jordan, Werner Heisenberg and Enrico Fermi, physicists came to believe that, in principle, it was possible to perform any computation for any physical process involving photons and charged particles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] However, further studies by Felix Bloch with Arnold Nordsieck, and Victor Weisskopf, in 1937 and 1939, revealed that such computations were reliable only at a first order of perturbation theory, a problem already pointed out by Robert Oppenheimer.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] At higher orders in the series infinities emerged, making such computations meaningless and casting doubt on the theory's internal consistency.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This suggested that special relativity and quantum mechanics were fundamentally incompatible.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Difficulties increased through the end of the 1940s.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Improvements in microwave technology made it possible to take more precise measurements of the shift of the levels of a hydrogen atom, later known as the Lamb shift and magnetic moment of the electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] These experiments exposed discrepancies that the theory was unable to explain.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] A first indication of a possible solution was given by Hans Bethe in 1947.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] He made the first non-relativistic computation of the shift of the lines of the hydrogen atom as measured by Willis Lamb and Robert Retherford.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Despite limitations of the computation, agreement was excellent.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The idea was simply to attach infinities to corrections of mass and charge that were actually fixed to a finite value by experiments.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In this way, the infinities get absorbed in those constants and yield a finite result with good experimental agreement.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This procedure was named renormalization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Based on Bethe's intuition and fundamental papers on the subject by Shin'ichirō Tomonaga, Julian Schwinger, Richard Feynman and Freeman Dyson, it was finally possible to produce fully covariant formulations that were finite at any order in a perturbation series of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Tomonaga, Schwinger, and Feynman were jointly awarded the 1965 Nobel Prize in Physics for their work in this area.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Their contributions, and Dyson's, were about covariant and gauge-invariant formulations of quantum electrodynamics that allow computations of observables at any order of perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Feynman's mathematical technique, based on his diagrams, initially seemed unlike the field-theoretic, operator-based approach of Schwinger and Tomonaga, but Dyson later showed that the two approaches were equivalent.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Renormalization, the need to attach a physical meaning at certain divergences appearing in the theory through integrals, became one of the fundamental aspects of quantum field theory and is seen as a criterion for a theory's general acceptability.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Even though renormalization works well in practice, Feynman was never entirely comfortable with its mathematical validity, referring to renormalization as a "shell game" and "hocus pocus".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Neither Feynman nor Dirac were happy with that way to approach the observations made in theoretical physics, above all in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] QED is the model and template for all subsequent quantum field theories.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] One such subsequent theory is quantum chromodynamics, which began in the early 1960s and attained its present form in the 1970s, developed by H.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] David Politzer, Sidney Coleman, David Gross and Frank Wilczek.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Near the end of his life, Richard Feynman gave a series of lectures on QED intended for the lay public.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] These lectures were transcribed and published as Feynman (1985), *QED: The Strange Theory of Light and Matter*, a classic non-mathematical exposition of QED from the point of view articulated below.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The key components of Feynman's presentation of QED are three basic actions.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] goes from one place and time to another place and time.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] An electron emits or absorbs a photon at a certain place and time.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] These actions are represented in the form of visual shorthand by the three basic elements of diagrams: a wavy line for the photon, a straight line for the electron and a junction of two straight lines and a wavy one for a vertex representing emission or absorption of a photon by an electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] These can all be seen in the adjacent diagram.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] As well as the visual shorthand for the actions, Feynman introduces another kind of shorthand for the numerical quantities called probability amplitudes.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The probability is the square of the absolute value of total probability amplitude, ${\text{probability}}=|f({\text{amplitude}})|^{2}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] If a photon moves from one place and time A to another place and time B , the associated quantity is written in Feynman's shorthand as $P(A{\text{ to }}B)$ , and it depends on only the momentum and polarization of the photon.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The similar quantity for an electron moving from C to D is written $E(C{\text{ to }}D)$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] It depends on the momentum and polarization of the electron, in addition to a constant Feynman calls *n*, sometimes called the "bare" mass of the electron: it is related to, but not the same as, the measured electron mass.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Finally, the quantity that tells us about the probability amplitude for an electron to emit or absorb a photon Feynman calls *j*, and is sometimes called the "bare" charge of the electron: it is a constant, and is related to, but not the same as, the measured electron charge *e*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] QED is based on the assumption that complex interactions of many electrons and photons can be represented by fitting together a suitable collection of the above three building blocks and then using the probability amplitudes to calculate the probability of any such complex interaction.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] It turns out that the basic idea of QED can be communicated while assuming that the square of the total of the probability amplitudes mentioned above (*P*(*A* to *B*), *E*(*C* to *D*) and *j*) acts just like our everyday probability (a simplification made in Feynman's book).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Later on, this will be corrected to include specifically quantum-style mathematics, following Feynman.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] If a virtual process involves a number of independent or concomitant sub-processes, then the probability amplitude of the total (compound) process is the **product** of the probability amplitudes of the sub-processes.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The indistinguishability criterion in (a) is very important: it means that there is *no observable feature present in the given system* that in any way "reveals" which alternative is taken.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In such a case, one cannot observe which alternative actually takes place without changing the experimental setup in some way (e.g. by introducing a new apparatus into the system).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Whenever one *is* able to observe which alternative takes place, one always finds that the *probability* of the event is the sum of the *probabilities* of the alternatives.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Indeed, if this were not the case, the very term "alternatives" to describe these processes would be inappropriate.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] What (a) says is that once the *physical means* for observing which alternative occurred is *removed*, one cannot still say that the event is occurring through "exactly one of the alternatives" in the sense of adding probabilities; one must add the amplitudes instead.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Similarly, the independence criterion in (b) is very important: it only applies to processes which are not "entangled".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Suppose we start with one electron at a certain place and time (this place and time being given the arbitrary label *A*) and a photon at another place and time (given the label *B*).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] A typical question from a physical standpoint is: "What is the probability of finding an electron at *C* (another place and a later time) and a photon at *D* (yet another place and time)?".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The simplest process to achieve this end is for the electron to move from *A* to *C* (an elementary action) and for the photon to move from *B* to *D* (another elementary action).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] From a knowledge of the probability amplitudes of each of these sub-processes – *E*(*A* to *C*) and *P*(*B* to *D*) – we would expect to calculate the probability amplitude of both happening together by multiplying them, using rule b) above.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This gives a simple estimated overall probability amplitude, which is squared to give an estimated probability.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] But there are other ways in which the result could come about.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The electron might move to a place and time *E*, where it absorbs the photon; then move on before emitting another photon at *F*; then move on to *C*, where it is detected, while the new photon moves on to *D*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The probability of this complex process can again be calculated by knowing the probability amplitudes of each of the individual actions: three electron actions, two photon actions and two vertexes – one emission and one absorption.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] We would expect to find the total probability amplitude by multiplying the probability amplitudes of each of the actions, for any chosen positions of *E* and *F*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] We then, using rule a) above, have to add up all these probability amplitudes for all the alternatives for *E* and *F*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] (This is not elementary in practice and involves integration.) But there is another possibility, which is that the electron first moves to *G*, where it emits a photon, which goes on to *D*, while the electron moves on to *H*, where it absorbs the first photon, before moving on to *C*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Again, we can calculate the probability amplitude of these possibilities (for all points *G* and *H*).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] We then have a better estimation for the total probability amplitude by adding the probability amplitudes of these two possibilities to our original simple estimate.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Incidentally, the name given to this process of a photon interacting with an electron in this way is Compton scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] An *infinite number* of other intermediate "virtual" processes exist in which photons are absorbed or emitted.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] For each of these processes, a Feynman diagram could be drawn describing it.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This implies a complex computation for the resulting probability amplitudes, but provided it is the case that the more complicated the diagram, the less it contributes to the result, it is only a matter of time and effort to find as accurate an answer as one wants to the original question.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] To calculate the probability of *any* interactive process between electrons and photons, it is a matter of first noting, with Feynman diagrams, all the possible ways in which the process can be constructed from the three basic elements.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Each diagram involves some calculation involving definite rules to find the associated probability amplitude.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] That basic scaffolding remains when one moves to a quantum description, but some conceptual changes are needed.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] One is that whereas we might expect in our everyday life that there would be some constraints on the points to which a particle can move, that is *not* true in full quantum electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] There is a nonzero probability amplitude of an electron at *A*, or a photon at *B*, moving as a basic action to *any other place and time in the universe*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] That includes places that could only be reached at speeds greater than that of light and also *earlier times*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Quantum mechanics introduces an important change in the way probabilities are computed.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Probabilities are still represented by the usual real numbers we use for probabilities in our everyday world, but probabilities are computed as the square modulus of probability amplitudes, which are complex numbers.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Feynman avoids exposing the reader to the mathematics of complex numbers by using a simple but accurate representation of them as arrows on a piece of paper or screen.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] (These must not be confused with the arrows of Feynman diagrams, which are simplified representations in two dimensions of a relationship between points in three dimensions of space and one of time.) The amplitude arrows are fundamental to the description of the world given by quantum theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] They are related to our everyday ideas of probability by the simple rule that the probability of an event is the *square* of the length of the corresponding amplitude arrow.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The rules as regards adding or multiplying, however, are the same as above.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] But where you would expect to add or multiply probabilities, instead you add or multiply probability amplitudes that now are complex numbers.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Addition and multiplication are common operations in the theory of complex numbers and are given in the figures.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Let the start of the second arrow be at the end of the first.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The sum is then a third arrow that goes directly from the beginning of the first to the end of the second.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The product of two arrows is an arrow whose length is the product of the two lengths.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The direction of the product is found by adding the angles that each of the two have been turned through relative to a reference direction: that gives the angle that the product is turned relative to the reference direction.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] That change, from probabilities to probability amplitudes, complicates the mathematics without changing the basic approach.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] But that change is still not quite enough because it fails to take into account the fact that both photons and electrons can be polarized, which is to say that their orientations in space and time have to be taken into account.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Therefore, *P*(*A* to *B*) consists of 16 complex numbers, or probability amplitude arrows.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] There are also some minor changes to do with the quantity *j*, which may have to be rotated by a multiple of 90° for some polarizations, which is only of interest for the detailed bookkeeping.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Associated with the fact that the electron can be polarized is another small necessary detail, which is connected with the fact that an electron is a fermion and obeys Fermi–Dirac statistics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The simplest case would be two electrons starting at *A* and *B* ending at *C* and *D*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The amplitude would be calculated as the "difference", *E*(*A* to *D*) × *E*(*B* to *C*) − *E*(*A* to *C*) × *E*(*B* to *D*), where we would expect, from our everyday idea of probabilities, that it would be a sum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Finally, one has to compute *P*(*A* to *B*) and *E*(*C* to *D*) corresponding to the probability amplitudes for the photon and the electron respectively.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] These are essentially the solutions of the Dirac equation, which describe the behavior of the electron's probability amplitude and the Maxwell's equations, which describes the behavior of the photon's probability amplitude.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] where a shorthand symbol such as $x_{A}$ stands for the four real numbers that give the time and position in three dimensions of the point labeled *A*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Thus there will be a way in which the electron travels to *C*, emits a photon there and then absorbs it again at *D* before moving on to *B*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Or it could do this kind of thing twice, or more.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In short, we have a fractal-like situation in which if we look closely at a line, it breaks up into a collection of "simple" lines, each of which, if looked at closely, are in turn composed of "simple" lines, and so on *ad infinitum*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This is a challenging situation to handle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] If adding that detail only altered things slightly, then it would not have been too bad, but disaster struck when it was found that the simple correction mentioned above led to *infinite* probability amplitudes.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In time this problem was "fixed" by the technique of renormalization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] However, Feynman himself remained unhappy about it, calling it a "dippy process", and Dirac also criticized this procedure, saying "in mathematics one does not get rid of infinities when it does not please you".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Within the above framework physicists were then able to calculate to a high degree of accuracy some of the properties of electrons, such as the anomalous magnetic dipole moment.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] However, as Feynman points out, it fails to explain why particles such as the electron have the masses they do.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] "There is no theory that adequately explains these numbers.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] We use the numbers in all our theories, but we don't understand them – what they are, or where they come from.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Mathematically, QED is an abelian gauge theory with the symmetry group U(1), defined on Minkowski space (flat spacetime).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The gauge field, which mediates the interaction between the charged spin-1/2 fields, is the electromagnetic field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] where $j^{\mu }$ is the conserved ${\text{U}}(1)$ current arising from Noether's theorem.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] For simplicity, $B_{\mu }$ has been set to zero, with no loss of generality.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] From this Lagrangian, the equations of motion for the $\psi$ and $A_{\mu }$ fields can be obtained.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] These arise most straightforwardly by considering the Euler-Lagrange equation for ${\bar {\psi }}$ .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Now, if we impose the Lorenz gauge condition $\partial _{\mu }A^{\mu }=0,$ the equations reduce to $\Box A^{\mu }=ej^{\mu },$ which is a wave equation for the four-potential, the QED version of the classical Maxwell equations in the Lorenz gauge.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This theory can be straightforwardly quantized by treating bosonic and fermionic sectors as free.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This permits us to build a set of asymptotic states that can be used to start computation of the probability amplitudes for different processes.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This technique is also known as the S-matrix, and $S_{fi}$ is therefore known as the S-matrix element.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Which can also be written in terms of an integral over the interaction Hamiltonian density ${\mathcal {H}}_{I}=e{\overline {\psi }}\gamma ^{\mu }\psi A_{\mu }$ .
