[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This evolution operator only has meaning as a series, and what we get here is a perturbation series with the fine-structure constant as the development parameter.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Despite the conceptual clarity of the Feynman approach to QED, almost no early textbooks follow him in their presentation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] When performing calculations, it is much easier to work with the Fourier transforms of the propagators.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Experimental tests of quantum electrodynamics are typically scattering experiments.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In scattering theory, particles' momenta rather than their positions are considered, and it is convenient to think of particles as being created or annihilated when they interact.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Feynman diagrams then *look* the same, but the lines have different interpretations.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The electron line represents an electron with a given energy and momentum, with a similar interpretation of the photon line.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] A vertex diagram represents the annihilation of one electron and the creation of another together with the absorption or creation of a photon, each having specified energies and momenta.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Using Wick's theorem on the terms of the Dyson series, all the terms of the S-matrix for quantum electrodynamics can be computed through the technique of Feynman diagrams.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] From them, computations of probability amplitudes are straightforwardly given.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] An example is Compton scattering, with an electron and a photon undergoing elastic scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] from which we can compute the cross section for this scattering.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The predictive success of quantum electrodynamics largely rests on the use of perturbation theory, expressed in Feynman diagrams.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] However, quantum electrodynamics also leads to predictions beyond perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In the presence of very strong electric fields, it predicts that electrons and positrons will be spontaneously produced, so causing the decay of the field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This process, called the Schwinger effect, cannot be understood in terms of any finite number of Feynman diagrams and hence is described as nonperturbative.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Mathematically, it can be derived by a semiclassical approximation to the path integral of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] that, being closed loops, imply the presence of diverging integrals having no mathematical meaning.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] To overcome this difficulty, a technique called renormalization has been devised, producing finite results in very close agreement with experiments.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] A criterion for the theory being meaningful after renormalization is that the number of diverging diagrams is finite.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] In this case, the theory is said to be "renormalizable".
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The reason for this is that to get observables renormalized, one needs a finite number of constants to maintain the predictive value of the theory untouched.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This is exactly the case of quantum electrodynamics displaying just three diverging diagrams.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This procedure gives observables in very close agreement with experiment as seen e.g. for electron gyromagnetic ratio.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Renormalizability has become an essential criterion for a quantum field theory to be considered as a viable one.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] All the theories describing fundamental interactions, except gravitation, whose quantum counterpart is only conjectural and presently under very active research, are renormalizable theories.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] An argument by Freeman Dyson shows that the radius of convergence of the perturbation series in QED is zero.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The basic argument goes as follows: if the coupling constant were negative, this would be equivalent to the Coulomb force constant being negative.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This would "reverse" the electromagnetic interaction so that *like* charges would *attract* and *unlike* charges would *repel*.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This would render the vacuum unstable against decay into a cluster of electrons on one side of the universe and a cluster of positrons on the other side of the universe.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] Because the theory is "sick" for any negative value of the coupling constant, the series does not converge but is at best an asymptotic series.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] From a modern perspective, we say that QED is not well defined as a quantum field theory to arbitrarily high energy.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The coupling constant runs to infinity at finite energy, signalling a Landau pole.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] The problem is essentially that QED appears to suffer from quantum triviality issues.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This is one of the motivations for embedding QED within a Grand Unified Theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This theory can be extended, at least as a classical field theory, to curved spacetime.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/quantum-electrodynamics] This arises similarly to the flat spacetime case, from coupling a free electromagnetic theory to a free fermion theory and including an interaction which promotes the partial derivative in the fermion theory to a gauge-covariant derivative.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] In quantum field theory, and specifically quantum electrodynamics, **vacuum polarization** describes a process in which a background electromagnetic field produces virtual electron–positron pairs that change the distribution of charges and currents that generated the original electromagnetic field.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] It is also sometimes referred to as the **self-energy** of the gauge boson (photon).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] It is analogous to the electric polarization of dielectric materials, but in vacuum without the need of a medium.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] The effects of vacuum polarization have been routinely observed experimentally since then as very well-understood background effects.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Vacuum polarization, referred to below as the one loop contribution, occurs with leptons (electron–positron pairs) or quarks.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Vacuum polarization was first discussed in papers by Paul Dirac and Werner Heisenberg in 1934.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] After developments in radar equipment for World War II resulted in higher accuracy for measuring the energy levels of the hydrogen atom, Willis Lamb made measurements of the Lamb shift and the anomalous magnetic dipole moment of the electron.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] These effects corresponded to the deviation from the value −2 for the spectroscopic electron *g*-factor that are predicted by the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Later, Hans Bethe theoretically calculated those shifts in the hydrogen energy levels due to vacuum polarization in 1947, on his return train ride from the Shelter Island Conference to Cornell University.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Effects of vacuum polarization were calculated to first order in the coupling constant by Robert Serber and Edwin Albrecht Uehling in 1935.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] According to quantum field theory, the vacuum between interacting particles is not simply empty space.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Rather, it contains short-lived virtual particle–antiparticle pairs (leptons or quarks and gluons).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] These short-lived pairs are called vacuum bubbles.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] It can be shown that they have no measurable impact on any process.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Virtual particle–antiparticle pairs can also occur as a photon propagates.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] In this case, the effect on other processes is measurable.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Such charged pairs act as an electric dipole.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] In the presence of an electric field, e.g., the electromagnetic field around an electron, these particle–antiparticle pairs reposition themselves, thus partially counteracting the field (a partial screening effect, a dielectric effect).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] The field therefore will be weaker than would be expected if the vacuum were completely empty.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] This reorientation of the short-lived particle–antiparticle pairs is referred to as vacuum polarization.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Extremely strong electric and magnetic fields cause an excitation of electron–positron pairs.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Maxwell's equations are the classical limit of the quantum electrodynamics which cannot be described by any classical theory.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] A point charge must be modified at extremely small distances less than the reduced Compton wavelength ${\bar {\lambda }}_{\text{c}}$ ( ${\textstyle \,={\frac {\hbar }{mc}}=3.86\times 10^{-13}{\text{ m}}}$ ).
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] This can be understood as a screening of a point charge by a medium with a dielectric permittivity, which is why the term vacuum polarization is used.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] When observed from distances much greater than ${\bar {\lambda }}_{\text{c}}$ , the charge is renormalized to the finite value q .
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] These effects break the linearity of Maxwell's equations and therefore break the superposition principle.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] The QED result for slowly varying fields can be written in non-linear relations for the vacuum.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] As of 2019, this polarization and magnetization has not been directly measured.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] The vacuum polarization is quantified by the self-energy or vacuum polarization tensor Π*μν*(*p*) which describes the dielectric effect as a function of the four-momentum *p* carried by the photon.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] Thus the vacuum polarization depends on the momentum transfer, or in other words, the electric constant is scale dependent.
[src:quantum-electrodynamics/vacuum-polarization] The tensor structure of Π*μν*(*p*) is fixed by the Ward identity.
